New Rules for the World Economy
CAMBRIDGE, MASS.: Suppose the world's leading politicians were to reconvene in Bretton Woods, New Hampshire, to design a new world economic order.
Naturally, they would primarily address today's issues: the eurozone crisis, global recovery, financial regulation, international macroeconomic imbalances, and so on. But addressing these questions would compel the assembled leaders to go beyond them and reconsider the overall solidity of global economic arrangements.
Here are seven principles for global economic steering, grounded in common sense, that they might agree upon.
(I discuss this in more detail in my new book, The Globalization Paradox.)
1. The markets must be deeply embedded in existing regulatory systems.
The notion that markets regulate themselves suffered a mortal blow during the recent financial crisis and should be laid to rest once and for all.
Markets need other societal institutions to support them.
They rely on courts, legal systems, and regulatory bodies to establish and enforce rules.
They depend on stabilization functions provided by central banks and countercyclical fiscal policy.
Sie brauchen die politische Akzeptanz, die von einer umverteilenden Besteuerung, Sicherheitsnetzen und Sozialversicherungen mit hervorgebracht wird.
Und all dies gilt genauso für globale Märkte.
2. Auf absehbare Zukunft dürfte eine demokratische Staatsführung weitgehend innerhalb nationaler politischer Gemeinwesen organisiert sein.
The national state lives on, even if it may be weakening, and remains essentially the only game in town.
The pursuit of a world government is a futile endeavor.
Dass die nationalen Regierungen erhebliche Kontrollgewalt an die transnationalem Institutionen abgeben, ist kaum zu erwarten; zudem würde eine Regelharmonisierung Gesellschaften mit unterschiedlichen Bedürfnissen und Präferenzen nichts nutzen.
Die Europäische Union könnte die einzige Ausnahme von diesem Axiom sein, obwohl ihre gegenwärtige Krise es eher zu belegen scheint.
Allzu oft verschwenden wir internationale Zusammenarbeit auf übertrieben ehrgeizige Ziele. Dabei kommen letztlich schwache Ergebnisse heraus, die den kleinsten gemeinsamen Nenner zwischen den großen Ländern darstellen.
Wenn internationale Zusammenarbeit „erfolgreich“ ist, bringt sie Regeln hervor, die entweder zahnlos sind oder die Präferenzen der mächtigeren Länder widerspiegeln.
Die Baseler Regeln über die Kapitalanforderungen und die Regeln der Welthandelsorganisation zu Subventionen, geistigem Eigentum und Investitionsmaßnahmen typisieren diese Art von übertriebenem Ehrgeiz.
We can strengthen the efficiency and legitimacy of globalization by supporting democratic processes in our own countries instead of destroying them.

#3 Pluralistic Prosperity: Acknowledging that the central institutional infrastructure of the world economy must be built at the national level gives individual countries the freedom to develop institutions that best meet their needs.
The USA, Europe, and Japan have produced comparable levels of prosperity over the long term.
However, their labor markets, corporate governance, antitrust regulations, social security systems, and financial systems differ significantly, and a succession of these "models" – one each decade – is then presented as the great success that others should emulate.
The most successful companies of the future will allow room for experiments and permit further evolution of their institutions.
A global economy that recognizes the necessity and value of institutional diversity will promote such experimentation and evolutionary development rather than suppress them.
#4 Countries have the right to protect their own rules and institutions.
The aforementioned principles may appear innocuous.
But they carry significant implications that collide with the prevailing views of globalization advocates.
A corresponding implication is the right of individual countries to protect their national institutional decisions.
The recognition of institutional diversity would be meaningless if countries did not have the means to shape and preserve their own institutions – in one word: to "protect" them.
We should therefore accept that countries can retain national rules – tax policy, financial regulation, labor standards, or rules to protect consumer health and safety – and that they may do so by erecting barriers at their borders if trade demonstrably threatens local practices that enjoy broad public support.
If the proponents of globalization are correct, the calls for such protective measures without evidence or backing will fail.
If they are mistaken, there is a safety valve so that competing values – the benefits of open economies and the benefits of retaining national regulations – can both be given adequate attention in public debates.
5. Countries have no right to impose their own institutions on others.
The use of restrictions in cross-border trade or finance to maintain values and rules in their own country should not be equated with using such measures to impose these values and rules on other countries.
The rules of globalization should not force Americans or Europeans to consume goods produced in a way that most citizens in those countries find unacceptable.
Similarly, they should not be allowed to use trade sanctions or other leverage to change labor market regulations, environmental policy, or financial regulation in other countries.
Countries have a right to diversity, not to enforced convergence.

6. International agreements on economic cooperation to regulate the interaction between national institutions: Relying on national states to provide the basic governance functions for the world economy does not mean we should forego international rules.
The Bretton Woods system, in the end, also had clear rules, albeit ones that were limited in scope and depth.
A complete free-for-all would benefit no one.
What we need are traffic rules for the world economy that help vehicles of different sizes, shapes, and speeds navigate around each other, rather than prescribing identical cars or uniform speed limits.
We should strive for a maximum level of globalization that is in harmony with the preservation of space for diversity within national institutional arrangements.
7. Undemocratic countries cannot be entitled to the same rights and privileges in the international economic order as democracies.
What lends attractiveness and legitimacy to the aforementioned principles is that they are based on democratic consultation – where such consultations actually take place, within the nation-states.
If states are not democratic, this structure falls apart.
We can no longer assume that their institutional arrangements reflect the preferences of their citizens.
For undemocratic states, therefore, other, less liberal rules must apply.
This is what the architects of the next world economic order must accept.
Most important is that they must accept the ultimate paradox illustrated by each of these principles: globalization works best when it is not taken too far.
